INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'de5f1e9f-652f-4972-bfb0-2f44def0ac51',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$seaborn Statistical Testing — CI Bars, p-Values, and When Each Tells the Truth$escape$,
  $escape$seaborn's `barplot` and `pointplot` already render 95% bootstrap confidence intervals by default — those error bars are your visual hypothesis test. Overlapping CIs suggest no significant difference; non-overlapping CIs suggest one likely exists. But 'likely' isn't a p-value.

For explicit significance, pair seaborn with `statannotations.Annotator`. It hooks into any seaborn categorical axis — `boxplot`, `violinplot`, `barplot` — and overlays significance brackets with stars or exact p-values. Pass the same `data`, `x`, `y`, and `order` kwargs to keep annotations aligned with your plot geometry.

Underneath, `statannotations` dispatches to scipy tests you choose via `configure(test=...)`. Use `'Mann-Whitney'` for non-normal distributions (tip amounts, latency data), `'t-test_ind'` when normality holds. In seaborn v0.12+, replace deprecated `ci=95` with `errorbar=('ci', 95)` in `barplot`/`pointplot`.

For regression, `sns.regplot` renders a shaded confidence band automatically — that's a 95% CI on the conditional mean, not a prediction interval. To widen it to prediction bands you need to leave seaborn and go to `statsmodels` directly. Know the difference before presenting results.$escape$,
  $escape$import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statannotations.Annotator import Annotator

tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")
order = ["Thur", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"]

ax = sns.boxplot(data=tips, x="day", y="tip", order=order)

pairs = [("Thur", "Fri"), ("Sat", "Sun"), ("Fri", "Sun")]
annotator = Annotator(ax, pairs, data=tips, x="day", y="tip", order=order)
annotator.configure(test="Mann-Whitney", text_format="star", loc="outside")
annotator.apply_and_annotate()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
